03908nam a22005775i 9780889207851DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061990xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892078517 a10.51644/97808892078512doi  a(DE-B1597)667922  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aNC242.R8bA4 1990eb 7aART0160102bisacsh04a741/.0921 aHayman, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJohn Ruskin and Switzerland /cJohn Hayman. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (151 p.) :b115 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tMap -- tIntroduction -- tTours of 1833 and 1835 -- tTours of the 1840s -- tHistoric Towns of Switzerland -- tOn the Old Road -- tAdditional Drawings of Selected Swiss Towns by John Ruskin -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn authoritative work interspersed with nearly one hundred of John Ruskin’s Swiss drawings recounts his lifelong interest in Switzerland. Hayman provides a chronological account of Ruskin’s visits to Switzerland from his earliest travels in 1833 and 1835 and his frequent tours of the 1840s to the final visits in the 1880s. Of particular concern is Ruskin’s intention between approximately 1855 and 1865 to engrave his own drawings of Swiss towns for a work illustrative of Swiss history. Drawings of the historic Swiss towns in which Ruskin was most interested — Baden, Bellinzona, Brugg, Fribourg, Geneva, Laufenburg, Lucerne, Neuchâtel, Rheinfelden, Schaffhausen, and Thun — are introduced by excerpts from John Murray’s A Handbook for Travellers in Switzerland (1856). Hayman has traced a great many Swiss drawings Ruskin referred to in his letters and diaries and has located twenty-three previously unpublished ones which appear in his book. Ruskin’s well-documented defence of J.M.W. Turner is also brought to light as the author has juxtaposed reproductions of Turner’s sketches of Swiss towns with drawings by Ruskin. This work will not only interest scholars and students of Ruskin but should also pique the interest of Turner scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFine Arts. 0aRuskin, John, 1819-1900xJourneysxSwitzerland. 0aRuskin, John, 1819-1900. 0aSwitzerland in art. 0aTurner, J.M.W. (Joseph Mallord William), 1775-1851xInfluence. 4aArt. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 7aART / Individual Artists / Artists' Books.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207851423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207851/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles